Ex. No: 10 — Sort and Filter Data Based on Multiple Conditions in Pandas
Aim

To sort and filter data in Pandas DataFrame.

Theory

Sorting arranges data in ascending or descending order.
Filtering extracts records satisfying conditions.

Software / Tools Required
•
Python 3.x
•
Anaconda Distribution
•
Jupyter Notebook / IDLE / Google Colab
•
Pandas Library

Program
import pandas as pd

# Creating DataFrame
data = {
    'Name': ['Ravi', 'Anu', 'Kumar', 'Divya', 'Arun', 'Meena'],
    'Department': ['AI&DS', 'CSE', 'AI&DS', 'ECE', 'CSE', 'AI&DS'],
    'Marks': [88, 92, 79, 85, 90, 95]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

print("Original DataFrame:")
print(df)

# Sorting
print("\nSorted by Marks:")
print(df.sort_values(by='Marks'))

# Multiple sorting
print("\nSorted by Department and Marks:")
print(df.sort_values(by=['Department', 'Marks'],
                     ascending=[True, False]))

# Single condition
print("\nMarks > 85:")
print(df[df['Marks'] > 85])

# Multiple conditions
print("\nAI&DS Students with Marks > 85:")
print(df[(df['Department'] == 'AI&DS') &
         (df['Marks'] > 85)])

         
Procedure
Import Pandas library.
Create DataFrame.
Display original dataset.
Sort by single column.
Sort by multiple columns.
Apply single filtering condition.
Apply multiple conditions.
Use logical operators.
Display filtered data.
Execute and verify output.




